#Text=Agüeybaná I
#Text=Agüeybaná

#Text=( died 1510 ) was the principal and most powerful cacique [ 4 ] [ lower-alpha 1 ] ( chief ) of the Taíno people in " Borikén " ( Puerto Rico ) when the Spanish first arrived on the island on November 19 , 1493 .

column1: #Text=Etymology
#Text=Agüeybana

#Text=, which has been interpreted by 19th and 20th century authors as meaning " The Great Sun " , was the hereditary title shared by the family that ruled the theocratic monarchy of Borikén , governing the hierarchy over the rest of the regional chiefs or caciques .
#Text=Like other nobiliary recognitions within Taíno culture , it was passed down through the maternal bloodline . [ 1 ]

#Text=The Spanish settlers Hispanicized the title to be the equivalent of the European concept of kings , with contemporary writers such as Juan de Castellanos [ 5 ] and Gonzalo Fernández de Oviedo y Valdés [ 6 ] employing the title of Rey Agüeybana ( English : " King Agüeybana " ) when referring to the second monarch to lead the Taíno during the 1510s . [ 7 ]

#Text=By the 1800s , the terms " king " and " cacique " were used exchangeably by both local and Spanish authors , [ 8 ] [ 9 ] but a resurgence in the interest concerning Taíno history during the 20th century led to the popularization of native words and the latter term gained more lexical prominence .
#Text=Arrival of the conquistadors
#Text=Agüeybaná received the Spanish conquistador Juan Ponce de León upon his arrival in 1508 .

#Text=According to an old Taíno tradition , Agüeybaná practiced the " guatiao , " a Taíno ritual in which he and Juan Ponce de León became friends and exchanged names . Ponce de León then baptized the cacique 's mother into Christianity and renamed her Inés . [ 10 ]
#Text=The cacique joined Ponce de León in the exploration of the island .

#Text=After this had been accomplished , Agüeybaná accompanied the conquistador to the island of La Española ( what today comprises the nations of the Dominican Republic and Haiti ) , where he was well received by the Governor Nicolás de Ovando . [ 11 ]
#Text=Agüeybaná 's actions helped to maintain the peace between the Taíno and the Spaniards , a peace which was to be short-lived . [ 10 ]
#Text=The hospitality and friendly treatment that the Spaniards received from Agüeybaná made it easy for the Spaniards to betray and conquer the island . [ 10 ]
#Text=After a short period of peace , the Taínos were forced to work in the island 's gold mines and in the construction of forts as slaves .
#Text=Many Taínos died as a result of the cruel treatment which they received . [ 10 ]
#Text=Death and aftermath
#Text=Upon Agüeybaná 's death in 1510 , his brother [ 1 ] [ 2 ] [ 3 ]
#Text=Güeybaná
#Text=( better known as Agüeybaná II ) became the most powerful Cacique in the island .
#Text=Agüeybaná II was troubled by the treatment of his people by the Spanish and attacked them in battle .
#Text=The Taínos were ultimately defeated at the Battle of Yagüecas . [ 12 ]
#Text=Taínos in Puerto Rico either abandoned the island , were forced to labor as slaves , or were killed by the Spaniards to what till recently was thought resulted in a complete extinction .
#Text=However , recent genetic studies , revealed that Taino blood/ancestry is still very much present in the genome of Puertoricans .
#Text=Said studies published in between 2018 and 2019 revealed a narrative more indicative of assimilation and migrations to nearby islands rather than extinction .
#Text=[ 13 ]
#Text=Many succumbed to the smallpox epidemic that attacked the islanders in 1519 . [ 10 ] [ 14 ]
#Text=Legacy
#Text=Agüeybaná is admired in Puerto Rico for his dedication to his people and attempting to keep the peace .
#Text=Puerto Rico has named many public buildings and streets after him :
#Text=The City of Bayamón has named a high school after him .
#Text=There is a street in Caguas that honors him .
#Text=An avenue in the Hato Rey area of San Juan is named after Agüeybaná .
#Text=Puerto Rico once had an equivalent to the Grammy Award which was awarded annually and was called the " Agüeybaná de Oro " ( The Golden Agüeybaná ) , in honor of the great cacique . [ 15 ]
#Text=Many songs and poems , by poets such as Juan Antonio Corretjer , among others , have been written about Agüeybaná .
